Big Data - Linear Regression & Neuron Networks¶

Lecturer: Nang Nguyen¶

Data: Car_Purchasing_Data.csv
You are working as a car salesman and you would like to develop a model to predict the total dollar amount that customers are willing to pay given the following attributes:

  • Customer Name
  • Customer e-mail
  • Country
  • Gender
  • Age
  • Annual Salary
  • Credit Card Debt
  • Net Worth

The model should predict:

  • Car Purchase Amount

# Import necessary libraries for plotting
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Step 1: Import necessary PySpark modules
from pyspark.sql import SparkSession

# Step 2: Create and configure the Spark session
spark = SparkSession.builder.appName("CarPurchaseAmountPrediction").getOrCreate()

# Set the log level to ERROR to reduce verbosity
spark.sparkContext.setLogLevel("ERROR")

       .withColumn("AnnualSalary", col("AnnualSalary").cast(DoubleType())) \
       .withColumn("CreditCardDebt", col("CreditCardDebt").cast(DoubleType())) \

df = df.na.drop()

In [4]:
# Assemble features into a single vector
feature_columns = ["Gender", "Age", "AnnualSalary", "CreditCardDebt"]
assembler = VectorAssembler(inputCols=feature_columns, outputCol="features")
df = assembler.transform(df)

# Standardize features
scaler = StandardScaler(inputCol="features", outputCol="scaledFeatures")
scaler_model = scaler.fit(df)
df = scaler_model.transform(df)

# Step 6: Split data into training and test sets
train_df, test_df = df.randomSplit([0.8, 0.2], seed=42)

# Step 7: Train a linear regression model
lr = LinearRegression(featuresCol="scaledFeatures", labelCol="CarPurchaseAmount")
lr_model = lr.fit(train_df)

# Step 8: Make predictions on the test set
predictions = lr_model.transform(test_df)

# Step 9: Evaluate the model
evaluator = RegressionEvaluator(labelCol="CarPurchaseAmount", predictionCol="prediction", metricName="rmse")
rmse = evaluator.evaluate(predictions)
print(f"Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE): {rmse}")

# Display a few example predictions
predictions.select("CarPurchaseAmount", "prediction").show(5)

# Step 10: Stop Spark session
spark.stop()

# Step 1: Import necessary libraries
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import tensorflow as tf
from keras.models import Sequential
from keras.layers import Dense, Dropout, Input
from keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

# Import necessary PySpark modules
from pyspark.sql import SparkSession
from pyspark.sql.functions import col, when, regexp_replace
from pyspark.sql.types import DoubleType

# Step 2: Create and configure the Spark session
spark = SparkSession.builder.appName("CarPurchaseAmountPrediction").getOrCreate()

# Set the log level to ERROR to reduce verbosity
spark.sparkContext.setLogLevel("ERROR")

# Step 3: Load data using PySpark
data_path = "./data/Car_Purchasing_Data.csv"  # Path to your dataset
df = spark.read.csv(data_path, header=True, inferSchema=True)

# Display the schema of the DataFrame to understand the data structure
df.printSchema()

# Clean column names by removing spaces and special characters
df = df.select([regexp_replace(col(c), " ", "").alias(c.replace(" ", "").replace(".", "").replace("-", "")) for c in df.columns])

# Convert necessary columns to numeric types
df = df.withColumn("Age", col("Age").cast(DoubleType())) \
       .withColumn("AnnualSalary", col("AnnualSalary").cast(DoubleType())) \
       .withColumn("CreditCardDebt", col("CreditCardDebt").cast(DoubleType())) \
       .withColumn("NetWorth", col("NetWorth").cast(DoubleType())) \
       .withColumn("CarPurchaseAmount", col("CarPurchaseAmount").cast(DoubleType()))

# Handle missing values
df = df.na.drop()

# Convert categorical columns to numeric (if any). For example, Gender column
df = df.withColumn("Gender", when(col("Gender") == "Male", 1).otherwise(0))

# Step 4: Convert to Pandas DataFrame for plotting
pdf = df.toPandas()

# Step 5: Create a pair plot using Seaborn
sns.pairplot(pdf, vars=["Gender", "Age", "AnnualSalary", "CreditCardDebt", "NetWorth", "CarPurchaseAmount"])
plt.show()

# Step 6: Prepare data for TensorFlow
# Select features and target variable
features = pdf[["Gender", "Age", "AnnualSalary", "CreditCardDebt", "NetWorth"]]
target = pdf["CarPurchaseAmount"]

# Scale the data
scaler = MinMaxScaler()
scaled_features = scaler.fit_transform(features)

# Split data into training and test sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(scaled_features, target, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# Step 7: Build and train the Keras model
model = Sequential()
model.add(Input(shape=(5,)))
model.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.3))
model.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.3))
model.add(Dense(1, activation='linear'))

model.summary()

model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='mean_squared_error', metrics=['mae'])

early_stopping = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=10, restore_best_weights=True)

history = model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=150, batch_size=20, validation_split=0.2, callbacks=[early_stopping], verbose=1)
